solutions.content:
- My intuition was to store the minimum element and the hash map 
- and if the element is true in the hash map then it is logical that the the element is already popped out of the set
- After popping any element I make it true in the hash map.
- When a new element is popped back into the set then I change the hash value of it to false
- And if the mini < addback element then I update the mini value
- Next time mini value gets popped but there can be residual elements that are already popped before, so I used a while loop to get the next mini element.
# Code
```
class SmallestInfiniteSet {
public:
    int mini;
    unordered_map<int,bool> mp;
    SmallestInfiniteSet() { 
        mini=1;               
    }

    int popSmallest() {
        int i=0;
        while(mp[mini+i]){
            i++;
        }
        mp[mini+i]=true;
        mini += i+1;
        return mini-1;
    }

    void addBack(int num) {
        if(mp[num]){
            mini=min(mini,num);
            mp[num]=false;
        }                 
    }
};
```
