# Approach
Anyone knowing TreeSet will solve this problem using TreeSet. But that doesn't give us efficient solution. We can make it efficient by using Boolean Buckets.


# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(N \log N)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(N)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
``` Java []
class SmallestInfiniteSet {
    boolean[] isBucketEmpty;
    int n = 1001;
    int smallestNum;
    public SmallestInfiniteSet() {
        isBucketEmpty = new boolean[n];
        smallestNum = 1;
    }

    public int popSmallest() {
        int currentSmallestNum = smallestNum;
        // make this bucket empty as we popped it
        isBucketEmpty[smallestNum] = true;
        // find next non empty bucket
        for(int i = smallestNum+1; i<n; i++) {
            if(!isBucketEmpty[i]){
                // this is our new smallestNum
                smallestNum = i;
                break;
            }
        }
        return currentSmallestNum;
    }

    public void addBack(int num) {
        // set the bucket to non empty
        isBucketEmpty[num] = false;
        // update smallestNum
        if(num<smallestNum) {
            smallestNum = num;
        }
        // same thing:
        // smallestNum = Math.min(smallestNum, num);
    }
}

