# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Infinite set is a huge set of numbers and to keep track of all the numbers which are present in the set takes more space. So, instead of storing all the numbers which are present in the set we will store the numbers which are not present.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- Create a HashSet which stores distinct numbers. **Start** pointer which will keep track of the starting point of the set.
- To remove the first element return the **start** pointer integer, add the number to **"removed"** set and iterate to the next valid number.
- To add the number back to the infinite set remove the element from the **"removed"** set.

# Code
```
class SmallestInfiniteSet {
    // Storing all the numbers from the infinite set takes huge amount of space so instead of that we will keep track of numbers which are been removed from set.

    Set<Integer> removed; // contains numbers which are removed from the infinite Set.
    int start;

    public SmallestInfiniteSet() {
        removed = new HashSet<Integer>();
        start = 1;      // start pointer
    }

    public int popSmallest() {
        int toRemove = start;  
        removed.add(start); // smallest number is the first number in the set.

        int i = start+1;

        // check for the elements which are not there in the infinite set and assign the next start

        while(i <= start + removed.size()){ 
            if(removed.contains(i)) i++;
            else break;
        }

        start = i;
        return toRemove;
    }

    public void addBack(int num) {
        removed.remove(num); // num is added back so remove it from the "removed" set
        if(num < start) start = num;
    }
}

/**
 * Your SmallestInfiniteSet object will be instantiated and called as such:
 * SmallestInfiniteSet obj = new SmallestInfiniteSet();
 * int param_1 = obj.popSmallest();
 * obj.addBack(num);
 */
```

