# Complexity
This is based on Python code. Other languages might be different.

- Time complexity:
    - popSmallest - O(log n)

        a. If the heap is not empty, it performs a heap pop operation using heapq.heappop(), which has a time complexity of O(log n), where n is the number of elements in the heap.

        b. If the heap is empty, it increments self.min_num by 1 and returns self.min_num - 1, which takes constant time.

        Therefore, the worst-case time complexity of popSmallest method is O(log n), where n is the number of elements in the heap.


    - addBack - O(log n)

        a. It checks if self.min_num is greater than num and num is not in the heap, which takes constant time.

        b. If the above condition is True, it performs a heap push operation using heapq.heappush(), which has a time complexity of O(log n), where n is the number of elements in the heap.

        Therefore, the worst-case time complexity of addBack method is O(log n), where n is the number of elements in the heap.

- Space complexity: O(n)
 n is the number of elements in the heap.

# Python
```
class SmallestInfiniteSet:

    def __init__(self):
        self.heap = []
        self.set = set()
        self.min_num = 1

    def popSmallest(self) -> int:
        if self.heap:
            num = heapq.heappop(self.heap)
            self.set.remove(num)
            return num
        self.min_num += 1
        return self.min_num - 1

    def addBack(self, num: int) -> None:
        if self.min_num > num and num not in self.set:
            self.set.add(num)
            heapq.heappush(self.heap, num)
```
