# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Keep a list (checkList) that contains the values we add back successfully. For AddBack operations lead to nothing, we don't add those values to checkList. <br>
X param is used to save the largest number being popped from the beginning. <br>
## Some notes
- If we try to add a value greater than X, it should be existing in the set so we won't add it to the set.
- Values in checkList must be identical (of course). That's why I checked those conditions before adding num to the set.
- The smallest value must be in the checkList or X++ (if checkList is empty). Because the checkList contains only values that at-least-once being popped from the set (the set now is X + 1, X + 2, ..., Inf.). If some values is added again to the set (which are also added to checkList), it must be the smallest ones and must be popped before X + 1.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
168ms to run 135 testcases, beat 72%

- Space complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
57.2MB to run 135 testcases, beat 72%

# Code
```
public class SmallestInfiniteSet {
    int X;
    List<int> checkList;
    public SmallestInfiniteSet() {
        X = 0;
        checkList = new List<int>();
    }

    public int PopSmallest() {
        if (checkList.Count == 0) {
            X++;
            return X;
        }
        var min = checkList.Min();
        checkList.Remove(min);
        return min;
    }

    public void AddBack(int num) {
        if (num <= X && !checkList.Contains(num)) {
            checkList.Add(num);
        }
    }
}

