solutions.content:
Nice little data structure problem we can solve in many ways - with the main challenge being how to keep track of the reinserted numbers when they are below our current minimum value (later: `curr`), so that we can quickly access them and pop the smallest one of them.

We might be tempted to use something like a linked list for this, but it would hardly be worth the overhead with a maximum cap of `1000` calls (which means we would never have to worry about `num > 1000`, even if that did not have the same maximum constraint as well).

We will solve this problem storing this information in a boolean array first and then in an ordered set to see what would perform better - keeping in mind it really depends from the test cases to see what would run faster (I would expect the array to win in all the cases where we do not have a very sparse collection of reinserted values)

For starters, we will declare at instance level:
* `curr`, our current value to be `return`ed, initially set to `1` (the very firts positive integer);
* `removed` is an array of `1001` booleans, initially all set to `false`.

The `constructor` will do nothing, while `popSmallest` will:
* advance `curr` by `1` position `while` we are on values that were popped already (ie: `removed[curr] == true`);
* mark `curr` as popped by setting `removed[curr]` to `true`;
* `return` `curr`.

`addBack` will be pretty plain:
* if `num < curr`, we will set `curr` to be `num`;
* in any case, mark `removed[num]` to be `false` (that won't do a thing when `curr > num`).

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$ (`popSmallest`), $$O(1)$$ (constructor and `addBack`)
- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$ (with `n` being the upper limit of our range)

# Code
```cpp
class SmallestInfiniteSet {
    int curr = 1;
    bool removed[1001] = {};
public:
    SmallestInfiniteSet() {}

    int popSmallest() {
        while (removed[curr]) curr++;
        removed[curr] = true;
        return curr;
    }

    void addBack(int num) {
        if (num < curr) curr = num;
        removed[num] = false;
    }
};
```

By comparison using a set `addedBack` to store all the numbers `< curr` we insert back runs a bit slower (~5ms more) due to the overhead of using a set with a relatively small range and burns some extra space:

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(log(n))$$ (`popSmallest` and `addBack`), $$O(1)$$ (constructor)
- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$ (with `n` being the upper limit of our range)

# Code
```cpp
class SmallestInfiniteSet {
    int curr = 1, res;
    set<int> addedBack;
public:
    SmallestInfiniteSet() {}

    int popSmallest() {
        if (addedBack.size()) {
            auto pos = begin(addedBack);
            res = *pos;
            addedBack.erase(pos);
            return res;
        }
        return curr++;
    }

    void addBack(int num) {
        if (num < curr) addedBack.insert(num);
    }
};
```

